{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511966"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:48:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:48:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11819"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11819"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.02,0.26,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103436"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85858"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1325"},{"type":"tags","id":"1654"},{"type":"tags","id":"1899"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11412"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11418"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103436"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man is brought in by his daughter to the Emergency Department in a regional centre without an MRI. He describes an acute onset of severe back pain that begun approximately 8 hours ago. The pain is located in the lumbar region. He has had difficulty walking due to weakness and is now confined to his wheelchair. He has not urinated in 8 hours, and has some fecal incontinence an hour ago. He was diagnosed with small cell lung cancer (SCLC) six months ago and had been undergoing chemotherapy and radiotherapy until two months ago, given he was not considered a surgical candidate due to co-morbidities. His medical history includes COPD, poorly controlled type 2 diabetes, active smoking, hypertension, two past myocardial infarctions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe appears to be in severe pain and has a blood pressure of 136/80 mmHg, pulse 104/min and temperature 37.9C. He is unable to stand up. A brief cranial nerve examination is normal. He has normal tone, sensation and reflexes in his upper limb with decreased power. He has decreased power, tone and areflexia in his lower limbs. There is sensory loss on the posterior leg, including buttocks, as well as over the genitals and inner thighs; there is also a loss of anal tone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"On the assumption that all the options are immediately available, which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent neurosurgical review","Lumbar puncture","CT spine","Bone scan","IV antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is showing signs of lumbar spinal cord compression, including leg weakness, hypotonia, areflexia and saddle anaesthesia. His urinary retention is also a symptom of this. Although spinal cord syndromes such as cauda equina syndrome are most frequently caused by degenerative change such as canal stenosis or disc protrusion , they can also be the result of compression to the lumbar spine from tumours. This patient has a history of SCLC, which has likely metastasised to the bone to cause compression. Spinal cord compression is an emergency and requires urgent surgery for decompression, which is why an \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent neurosurgery consult\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate and must be the initial action taken in the management of this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Elumbar puncture \u003C/strong\u003Emay be useful in certain situations to determine potential causes of neurological issues, it will not assist in confirming the diagnosis of, or managing, the patient\u0027s cauda equina syndrome. In fact, it could be very dangerous in this situation..\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA CT spine \u003C/strong\u003Eis the second line imaging modality for diagnosis of cauda equina syndrome. It is the incorrect option in this case as it would not be the preferred option prior to an urgent neurosurgery consult or MRI spine (which is not available in this setting). A CT would only be done if the transport was organised, and there is spare time; however, the neurosurgical referral would be a higher priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone scan \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be useful in this situation. It would instead be useful in identifying areas of bone in which the cancer for this patient has spread. However, while this investigation may serve to be useful in understanding the extent of the patient\u0027s cancer spreading, it is not relevant in the immediate management of the emergency situation that is this patient\u0027s cauda equina syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile it may be tempting to provide \u003Cstrong\u003EIV antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003Eas a safety measure considering the urinary retention and fecal incontinence, they are not yet indicated for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cauda equina syndrome is a medical emergency.","The best imaging to diagnose cauda equina syndrome is an MRI spine, but implantable cardiac defibrillators are an absolute contraindication.","Cauda equina syndrome presents with symptoms including acute severe back pain, weakness in lower limb, urinary/bowel incontinence or urinary retention and saddle anaesthesia."],"references":["Gardner A, Gardner E, Morley T. Cauda equina syndrome: a review of the current clinical and medico-legal position. European Spine Journal [Internet]. 2010 [cited 17 August 2022];20(5):690-697. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3082683/","McNamee J, Flynn P, O\u0027Leary S, Love M, Kelly B. Imaging in Cauda Equina Syndrome \u2013 A Pictorial Review. Ulster Med J [Internet]. 2013 [cited 17 August 2022];82(2):100-108. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3756868/","Long B, Koyfman A, Gottlieb M. Evaluation and management of cauda equina syndrome in the emergency department. Am J Emerg Med. 2020 Jan;38(1):143-148. doi: 10.1016/j.ajem.2019.158402. Epub 2019 Aug 20. PMID: 31471075."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85858"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85858"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T14:10:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T14:10:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4424"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103436"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83